  "summary": "The core causal structure describes a feedback system in which AI-assisted development increases change volume to the point where traditional code review capacity is overwhelmed, particularly because reviewers lack fluency in AI-chosen libraries. The proposed three-layer model addresses this by routing different defect classes to different mechanisms: Layer 1 automation catches correctness and regressions; Layer 2 behavioral review catches UX and experiential defects while building product knowledge; Layer 3 structural review handles high-risk change types on a triggered basis. However, the behavioral layer introduces its own causal risks — author curation of the walkthrough threatens scope integrity, reduced implementation knowledge transfer increases bus factor risk, and the social dynamics of reviewer engagement are the single largest determinant of whether the system provides real value or devolves into rubber-stamping. Scope integrity mechanisms (diff-coverage linking, spot checks, walkthrough freshness requirements) and formal specification coverage act as countervailing forces against these degradation pathways, but the document explicitly acknowledges the system is not self-stabilizing and will drift toward superficiality without active maintenance."
